Rating: 3
Very good recipe. I always brine pork when I grill. It defiantly makes a difference. I used boneless sirloin chops and it came out great. For those who think brining is too salty, two points. 1) The thinner the chop, the less time it takes to brine. E.g. 2-inch bone-in chops can sit for 10 hours. 1-inch boneless chops only need 4 hours. 2) Rinse the meat under cold water after you brine them. The solution is already in the meat, so you aren't rinsing it off.

