Rating: 3
After years of failed pork chops on the grill and smoker, I have finally found one that I like! This recipe is so easy that it doesn't seem like it should be this good. Here are the specifics of my variations: 1. Boneless 1+" thick loin chops from Costco 2. Used a tad of maple syrup instead of the molasses 3. Anchor Steam Stout for the marinade 4. Cut the salt in the final rub by 1/2 and added one TBS of olive oil. Other suggestions: After marinating the chops, dry them really well with paper towels - this will avoid "seepage" of coagulated proteins and brine onto the beatiful grilled surface of the chops once they start cooking. Grilling technique (and this may be the most important!): Use a Weber kettle BBQ if you are lucky enough to have one. IMO, this recipe will NOT be as good prepared over a direct flame (i.e. a gas-fired BBQ). I prepared my coals (~60 of them)in the center of the grill, seared the chops on each side, then moved the coals into a ring around the outside edge of the lower grate. Then I added a small chunk of hickory (that had soaked in water for a couple of hours). I placed the chops into the center so that they were not directly above the coals, and grilled them for about 30 minutes with the top and bottom air vents open but the lid on, turning the chops once. The results were beautifully-bronzed chops with nice grill marks, incredibly tender, and flavorful. Believe it or not, I served them with a little bit of apple sauce - it was delicious!

